article.description:
Crystal Robinson scored 16 points and Becky
Hammon had 15 to rally the New York Liberty over the last-place San Antonio Silver Stars 64-62 on Sunday.
article.headline: Liberty end three-game skid
article.linkText: Silver lining: Liberty edge Stars to snap losing skid
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Overcoming poor first-half shooting, Crystal
Robinson and Becky Hammon helped snap New York's three-game losing
streak and keep pace in the tightly contested Eastern Conference.

Robinson scored 16 points and Hammon added 15 to rally the
Liberty past the last-place San Antonio Silver Stars 64-62 on
Sunday.

"We have great clutch shooters, so it was only a matter of
time," Hammon said. "We had 17 points at the half, and that's
just not like us at all. In the second half, we calmed down and
shot the ball better."

Robinson scored 14 second-half points -- including four
3-pointers -- and Hammon made a pair of driving layups in the final
27 seconds.

The Liberty (15-15) moved into sole possession of third place in
the East, one-half game behind Charlotte and Connecticut with a
week remaining in the regular season.

"We had to win this game," Hammon said. "A loss would have
been a backbreaker. It's playoff mentality right now and we just
have to keep rolling."

LaToya Thomas scored 17 points, Shannon Johnson had 14 and
Adrienne Goodson added 13 points and eight rebounds for San
Antonio.

The Liberty shot 28 percent and trailed 27-17 at the break, a
halftime season-low at home. New York was 16-for-26 (62 percent) in
the second half, including 7-of-13 on 3-pointers.

"We had some wide-open shots. We did a much better job
executing in the second half," Liberty interim coach Pat Coyle
said. "We made some adjustments and that's what happens. We got
good shots and we finally knocked some down."

Trailing 41-31 with just under 14 minutes remaining, New York
went on a 16-4 run over the next six minutes. The spurt included
three consecutive 3-pointers by the Liberty, including two by
Robinson. Her second gave New York a 44-43 lead with 9:09
remaining, its first advantage since 6-5.

"She was huge tonight," Coyle said of Robinson, who is
averaging 15.2 points in five games since the monthlong Olympic
break. "She probably has been our most consistent performer since
we have gotten back."

Elena Baranova, who scored 13 points for the Liberty, followed
with a 3 to give New York its biggest lead of the game, 47-43.

San Antonio, owners of the league's worst record (8-24), took a
three-point lead three times in the final four minutes. After
Thomas hit a pair of free throws to stretch the Silver Stars' lead
to 60-57 with 1:22 left, Robinson tied it again for the Liberty
with a 22-footer 19 seconds later.

"We could have stopped at any point given that we are playing
just for pride right now," San Antonio coach Shell Dailey said.
"I'm just happy we gave ourselves a chance. We missed some key
defensive things, but for the most part we played well."

Hammon's layup with 26.9 seconds left was her 1,500th career
point, and gave New York a 62-60 lead.

Shannon Johnson's two free throws tied it with 14.7 seconds
left, but Hammon made the game-winning layup with 8.4 seconds left.

"I just saw an opening and went for it," Hammon said. "Our
post players did a nice job of getting me open so I could get the
ball."

The Silver Stars used an 11-0 run, capped by Johnson's
3-pointer, to take a 22-11 lead with 9:45 left in the first half.
Thomas had nine points at the break.

The Liberty host Indiana on Thursday in the finale at Radio City
Music Hall. New York is 4-1 at the famed concert hall, and will
return to Madison Square Garden for the regular-season finale
against Washington on Sept. 19.

La'Keshia Frett and Erin Thorn started in place of Bethany
Donaphin and Baranova, who violated undisclosed team rules.
